# AI Evaluation Guidance

Distilled from [Anthropic — Demystifying evals for AI agents](https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/demystifying-evals-for-ai-agents) and [Vercel — Eval-driven development](https://vercel.com/blog/eval-driven-development-build-better-ai-faster).

## Core concepts

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Eval suite** | Collection of tasks measuring a specific capability or behaviour |
| **Task** | Single test with defined inputs and success criteria |
| **Trial** | One attempt at a task (run multiple — model output varies between runs) |
| **Grader** | Logic that scores one aspect of agent performance; a task can have many |
| **Transcript** | Full record of a trial: outputs, tool calls, reasoning, intermediate results |
| **Outcome** | Final environment state, not what the agent *said* it did |

## Grader types — choose the right one

### Code-based graders (prefer where possible)
- Fast, cheap, objective, reproducible
- Use for: JSON shape validation, field constraints, word budgets, regex checks, tool-call verification, token/iteration counts
- Weakness: brittle to valid variations; can't assess subjective quality

### LLM-as-judge graders (where code can't reach)
- Handles freeform output, open-ended tasks, nuance
- Use for: reasoning quality, signal interpretation, action appropriateness, coherence
- **Calibrate against human judgement** — run periodic spot-checks to verify LLM grades match expert opinion
- Give the judge a structured rubric with clear dimensions; grade each dimension with an isolated call rather than one call for all dimensions
- Give the judge an escape hatch ("Unknown" / "Insufficient information") to avoid hallucinated grades
- LLM evals cost 1.5–2× more than code-based — use code graders first, LLM graders for what remains

### Human graders (for calibration, not routine)
- Gold standard but slow and expensive
- Use to: calibrate LLM graders, validate subjective tasks, resolve inter-rater disagreement

## Capability vs regression evals

| Type | Purpose | Expected pass rate | Lifecycle |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Regression** | "Does it still work?" | ~100% | Run on every deploy; failures = something broke |
| **Capability** | "How good is it?" | Starts low, hill-climb | Run on prompt/model changes; measures improvement |

Capability evals that reach high pass rates **graduate** into the regression suite.

## Task design

1. **Start with 20–50 tasks** drawn from real failures — don't wait for hundreds
2. **Source from production** — manual checks, bug reports, support queue, `agent_logs`
3. **Make tasks unambiguous** — two domain experts should independently reach the same pass/fail verdict
4. **Create reference solutions** — a known-good output that passes all graders (proves the task is solvable)
5. **Balance positive and negative cases** — test both "should trigger" and "should NOT trigger" to avoid one-sided optimisation
6. **Build partial credit** — an agent that gets 3/4 steps right is meaningfully better than one that fails immediately

## Grader design

- **Grade outcomes, not paths** — don't require a specific sequence of tool calls; agents find valid approaches you didn't anticipate
- **Make graders cheat-resistant** — passing should require genuinely solving the problem
- **0% pass@100 usually means a broken task**, not an incapable agent — double-check the spec and graders
- **Read the transcripts** — you won't know if graders work until you read trials and verify grades match your judgement

## Non-determinism

Run multiple trials per task (≥3 for capability evals, 1 for regression).

| Metric | Measures | Use when |
|---|---|---|
| **pass@k** | P(≥1 success in k trials) — rises with k | One success matters (coding, research) |
| **pass^k** | P(all k trials succeed) — falls with k | Consistency matters (user-facing agents) |

## The eval-driven flywheel (Vercel)

```
Evals → identify weakness → improve prompt/model → re-eval → confirm improvement
  ↑                                                              ↓
  ← ← ← ← ← ← ← production feedback ← ← ← ← ← ← ← ← ← ← ←
```

1. **Evals** give data-driven signal on strengths and weaknesses
2. **Data** — evals pinpoint data gaps; high-quality data fuels fine-tuning
3. **Models & strategies** — evals enable rapid A/B testing of models, prompts, RAG strategies
4. **Feedback** — user feedback (error reports, implicit behaviour, explicit ratings) feeds back into eval tasks

## Eval harness principles

- Each trial starts from a **clean, isolated environment** — no shared state between runs
- The eval agent should function **the same as production** — same tools, same prompts, same constraints
- Log results with enough metadata to reconstruct the trial (inputs, transcript, grader scores, model version, prompt version)
- Track **latency, token usage, cost per task, error rates** as baseline metrics on every run

## Eval suite health

- **Monitor for saturation** — a 100% suite tracks regressions but gives no improvement signal; add harder tasks
- **Maintain continuously** — eval suites are living artifacts; update as the product and model evolve
- **Practice eval-driven development** — define evals for planned capabilities *before* the agent can fulfil them, then iterate until it can

## Anti-patterns

- Writing evals only after launch (requirements drift, reverse-engineering success criteria)
- Testing only happy paths (one-sided optimisation)
- Grading tool-call sequences instead of outcomes (brittle, punishes creativity)
- Taking eval scores at face value without reading transcripts
- Using a single LLM call to grade all dimensions (use isolated calls per dimension)
- Ignoring cost: LLM graders at 1.5–2× code graders adds up — prefer code where possible
